This paper deals with the complexity of manipulation, control, and bribery in election systems, which are topics that fall under computational social choice (cs.GT). The paper also involves analyzing the complexity of algorithms for solving these problems, which is a common theme in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of dichotomy theorems and complexity classes suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the study of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper involves analyzing the properties of scoring systems, which is a topic in machine learning and data analysis (cs.LG). Finally, the paper involves analyzing the complexity of decision-making processes, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
